in building spatial resilience after disasters -- tResidents’ participation in rebuilding more resilient space -- tSpatial planning and dealing with uncertainties associated with future disasters -- tChange-proof cities and regions – an integrated concept for tackling key challenges for spatial development -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPopulation shifts and an increase in the number of natural (and man-made) disasters are having a profound effect on urban and rural habitats globally. This book brings together for the first time the experiences and knowledge of international contributors from academia, research, policy and practice to discuss the role of spatial planning after significant disasters. It highlights on-going efforts to improve spatial resilience across the globe and predicts future trends. Comparisons from five countries including Japan, the US, Indonesia, Slovakia and Germany, highlight the influence of significant disasters on spatial planning and spatial resiliency under different legal-administrative and cultural frameworks.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBuildingsxProtection. 0aCity planning. 0aDisasters. 0aHazard mitigation. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh1 aBirkmann, Joern, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChandrasekhar, Divya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDjalante, Riyanti, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDzurdženík, Ján, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinn, Donovan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarschagen, Matthias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular